{"add":{"doc":{"id":"b195331882713a4407ef5d254a0f4b7b93ab3490de02c42814f56b2e2937d423","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Howler_monkey.jpg/220px-Howler_monkey.jpg","previous":["In South America, squirrel monkeys associate with capuchin monkeys.[99] This may have more to do with foraging benefits to the squirrel monkeys than anti-predation benefits.[99]","The red-tailed monkey associates with several species, including the Western red colobus, blue monkey, Wolf's mona monkey, mantled guereza, black crested mangabey and Allen's swamp monkey.[93] Several of these species are preyed upon by the common chimpanzee.[98]"],"after":["Primates have advanced cognitive abilities: some make tools and use them to acquire food and for social displays;[100][101] some have sophisticated hunting strategies requiring cooperation, influence and rank;[102] they are status conscious, manipulative and capable of deception;[103] they can recognise kin and conspecifics;[104][105] and they can learn to use symbols and understand aspects of human language including some relational syntax and concepts of number and numerical sequence.[106][107][108] Research in primate cognition explores problem solving, memory, social interaction, a theory of mind, and numerical, spatial, and abstract concepts.[109] Comparative studies show a trend towards higher intelligence going from prosimians to New World monkeys to Old World monkeys, and significantly higher average cognitive abilities in the great apes.[110][111] However, there is a great deal of variation in each group (e.g., among New World monkeys, both spider[110] and capuchin monkeys[111] have scored highly by some measures), as well as in the results of different studies.[110][111]"]}}}